<br />
Artifact (1):<br />
Palantir    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Really just submitting this for archival purposes... <br />
<br />
This is a fun little deck that my local playgroup kept coming back to over the last couple months, eventually transforming into a Ferny deck, and later shelving it altogether, deeming it "too risky."<br />
<br />
The Goal: When your opponent reaches site 9, you want these cards in your hand: <br />
<br />
Saruman<br />
Runner<br />
Runner<br />
Warrior<br />
Forger<br />
Fell Voice (or Captain if FV is already down)<br />
Hate And Anger<br />
Hate And Anger <br />
<br />
And these cards in your draw deck, to be drawn by Hate and Anger: 3x Ravager, 3x Lieutenant.<br />
<br />
Saruman, six fierce Uruks, and four other minions can come down for as little as twelve twilight. Saruman will then retrieve your Snows and Frost, and the Warrior/Forger combo prevents archery. <br />
<br />
The Setup: Everything that is not directly involved in the Final Shadow Hand is generally either stacking cards or trying to cover some particular weakness.  <br />
<br />
The fellowship is essentially trying to: 1) Stay alive  (it usually only needs to make it to site four or five). 2) Make full use of Gimli, DoE -- this is why the Gaffer&#39;s Pipe is so important, as it allows multiple "stacks" per turn. 3) Draw/discard cards to ensure that the deck is depleted in time.<br />
<br />
Admittedly, this deck lives and dies by the draw, but doesn&#39;t every deck? This deck is just more comfortable with its risks: it knows when everything is going to hell, and similarly it knows when it is headed towards inevitable victory. Kinda sucks the drama out of the game, but it&#39;s fun if you&#39;re the type who enjoys complete control. <br />
<br />
Anyway, try it out some time if you get nostalgic for FotR block, or, like me, can&#39;t yet afford to enter TTT block -- it&#39;s especially rewarding when played against unsuspecting opponents. I suppose you could probably try a modified version in "open block" utilizing the Saruman-grabbing site 9, but I&#39;ll leave that to somebody else, at least for now.<br />
<br />
<br />
Credits:<br />
Ryan Granger - Various nuanced innovations; playtesting.<br />
Todd Vandewalker - Playtesting; refusal to play at Worlds :) <br />
